w needs generally please contact us on either 01872 241414 or by email employment@nalders.co.uk\r\n','','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article','0','35','35','und','0','Businesses should take note of an Employment Appeal Tribunal (EAT) decision which suggests that a requirement to attend an interview has the potential to disadvantage a disabled employee. The decision also highlights how an employer can make reasonable adjustments to remove that disadvantage. However, the EAT makes it clear that appointment to the post is not automatically required. It will be for the employer to consider how it can assess the disabled employee alongside other candidates in the particular circumstances.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the EAT upheld an employment tribunal decision that an employer failed to make reasonable adjustments for a disabled employee in a redundancy exercise. The employee''s disability meant that he was unable to attend administrative meetings, which the tribunal held included interviews. The tribunal found that the employer failed to consider alternative ways of assessing his suitability for roles into which he might have been redeployed as an alternative to redundancy.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to know more or to discuss any employment law needs generally please contact us on either 01872 241414 or by email employment@nalders.co.uk.\r\n','Businesses should take note of an Employment Appeal Tribunal (EAT) decision which suggests ','filtered_html'),('node','article','0','40','40','und','0','Today workers won a ground-breaking case at the Employment Appeal Tribunal that could affect how millions are paid holiday pay.  Currently, when calculating holiday pay, only basic pay is taken into account. The ruling today in the Bear Scotland v Fulton case could open the floodgates to employees becoming entitled to additional holiday pay if their usual salary also consists of any overtime or commission.\r\n\r\nThe cases centred on the interpretation of the EU-wide Working Time Directive (which gives employees 20 days paid holiday a year), particularly the Working Time Regulations which were implemented in 1998 in the UK. The tribunal ruling suggests that UK businesses have been interpreting the directive incorrectly, and holiday pay should be paid on a basic salary or an average salary over a period of time. \r\n\r\nThe ruling could now lead to similar claims for back-pay of owed holiday pay over the past 16 years which could run into millions of pounds for UK companies.  However claims for back-pay will be out of time if there has been a break of more than three months between each successive underpayment.\r\n\r\nBusiness will be hoping that this is not the final word on the matter and that the decision will be appealed and the EAT have granted permission for an appeal to the Court of Appeal.  Further, Business Secretary Vince Cable has announced he is setting up a new taskforce to assess the impact of the ruling and the early indications are that the taskforce will be seeking to limit the impact for the benefit of businesses rather than employees.\r\n\r\nIf you have any concerns regarding the above issue or any employment law needs generally please contact us on 01872 241414 or employment@nalders.co.uk.\r\n','Today workers won a ground-breaking case at the Employment Appeal Tribunal that could affect how millions are paid holiday pay. ','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','article','0','41','41','und','0','On 1 December 2014 the Shared Parental Leave Regulations will come into effect and will apply to all employees who expect to take leave for a child born or adopted after 5 April 2015.\r\n\r\nThe Regulations are complex but in essence they mean that maternity leave, formerly the exclusive preserve of the mother, can now be carved up and shared between the mother and a second “entitled” person. The second person must be either the father of the child or married to, in a civil partnership with or the partner of the mother.\r\n\r\nEmployers must make sure that employees know how to apply for shared parental leave and must meet the statutory minimum requirements.  In most cases, employers will choose to review and rewrite procedures, policies and forms so that their adherence to the Regulations is clear.\r\nIf you have any concerns regarding the above issue or any employment law needs generally please contact us on 01872 241414 or employmentlaw@nalders.co.uk.\r\n','On 1 December 2014 the Shared Parental Leave Regulations will come into effect and will apply to all employees who expect to take leave for a child born or adopted after 5 April 2015','filtered_html'),('node','article','0','42','42','und','0','Since April 2007, a deposit paid under an Assured Shorthold Tenancy (AST) must be protected within 30 days of the commencement of the tenancy. The landlord or his agent must also send the tenant the prescribed information required by the Deposit scheme and a copy of the Deposit Protection Certificate, again within 30 days of receipt of the deposit. A landlord cannot serve a Notice Requiring Possession unless the deposit has been protected and the prescribed information sent.\r\n\r\nAlthough this is old news, some landlords still do not protect the deposit and fewer still send the tenant the prescribed information.\r\n\r\nRecent changes to the relevant Claim Form mean it is now immediately obvious to the Court and to the tenant whether the landlord has complied with his obligations: a landlord must now send the Court the Deposit Protection Certificate, and also state the date on which the prescribed information was sent to the tenant.\r\n\r\nA tenant may apply to the court under the Housing Act 2004 if the deposit has not been protected or the prescribed information has not been sent in time. If the tenant applies to court the judge must order the landlord to pay the tenant back the deposit, and can order him to pay 3 times the amount of the deposit.\r\n\r\nWatch out – following the Court of Appeal decisions in Superstrike Ltd -v- Marino Rodrigues and Charalambous v NG, even if the original AST started before the mandatory deposit protection came into effect the deposit has to be protected when the fixed term ends and the tenancy continues on a statutory periodic basis because that periodic tenancy is a ‘new’ tenancy. So for pre-2007 tenancies, the deposit has to be protected or returned before a Notice Requiring Possession can be served.\r\n\r\nIf you have any questions regarding the above changes or any legal needs generally please contact us on 01872 241414 or by email. \r\n','Since April 2007, a deposit paid under an Assured Shorthold Tenancy (AST) must be protected within 30 days of the commencement of the tenancy. The landlord or his agent must also send the tenant the prescribed information required by the Deposit scheme and a copy of the Deposit Protection Certificate, again within 30 days of receipt of the deposit. A landlord cannot serve a Notice Requiring Possession unless the deposit has been protected and the prescribed information sent.','filtered_html');
INSERT INTO `field_data_body` VALUES ('node','blog','0','89','89','und','0','Please join us in Truro on 12 February 2015 at our Employment Law Seminar to look ahead to 2015 and the key matters which employers will have to look out for.\r\nWe will focus particularly on the new Shared Parental Leave Regulations which will apply to babies born or adopted from April onwards.  We will also discuss the recent holiday pay ruling and what it means in practical terms both in terms of past amends and any future holiday payments made by employers.\r\nVenue:     	Truro, to be confirmed\r\nTiming:	8:00am – Registration; tea and coffee, breakfast rolls\r\n 	8:15am – Seminar commences\r\n 	9:30am – Seminar ends followed by pastries and networking\r\nFee:	Free for our existing EPS clients otherwise £35 plus VAT (£42) per person. Invoices will be raised once your booking is confirmed.\r\nOur seminars are designed for business owners, managers, human resources professionals and anyone aiming to gain a practical knowledge of key employment issues.\r\nIf you would like to book a space or request further information, please contact us as soon as possible by email to mej@nalders.co.uk or by calling and asking for Melanie Jenkin on 01872 241414. Please advise us of any special mobility or dietary requirements you may have.\r\n','Please join us in Truro on 12 February 2015 at our Employment Law Seminar to look ahead to 2015 and the key matters which employers will have to look out for.','filtered_html'),('node','article','0','90','90','und','0','Please join us in Truro on 12 February 2015 at our Employment Law Seminar to look ahead to 2015 and the key matters which employers will have to look out for.\r\n\r\nWe will focus particularly on the new Shared Parental Leave Regulations which will apply to babies born or adopted from April onwards.  We will also discuss the recent holiday pay ruling and what it means in practical terms both in terms of past amends and any future holiday payments made by employers.\r\n\r\nVenue:     Truro, to be confirmed\r\nTiming:	8:00am – Registration; tea and coffee, breakfast rolls\r\n 	        8:15am – Seminar commences\r\n 	        9:30am – Seminar ends followed by pastries and networking\r\n\r\nFee:	Free for our existing EPS clients otherwise £35 plus VAT (£42) per person. Invoices will be raised once your booking is confirmed.\r\nOur seminars are designed for business owners, managers, human resources professionals and anyone aiming to gain a practical knowledge of key employment issues.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to book a space or request further information, please contact us as soon as possible by email to mej@nalders.co.uk or by calling and asking for Melanie Jenkin on 01872 241414. Please advise us of any special mobility or dietary requirements you may have.\r\n','Please join us in Truro on 12 February 2015 at our Employment Law Seminar to look ahead to 2015 and the key matters which employers will have to look out for.','filtered_html');
